\begin_layout Subsection
Beta Transformation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After exactly one iteration of the beta shift, all initial points 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta/2\le x\le1$
\end_inset

 are swept up into the domain 
\begin_inset Formula $0\le x<\beta/2$
\end_inset

, and never leave.
 Likewise, the range of the iterated beta shift is 
\begin_inset Formula $0\le x<\beta/2$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, an alternative representation of the beta shift, filling the entire
 unit square, can be obtained by dividing both the domain and range by 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta/2$
\end_inset

 to obtain the function
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
t_{\beta}(u)=\begin{cases}
\beta u & \mbox{ for }0\le u<\frac{1}{\beta}\\
\beta u-1 & \mbox{ for }\frac{1}{\beta}\le u\le1
\end{cases}\label{eq:beta transform}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This can be written more compactly as 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{\beta}\left(x\right)=\beta x\mod1$
\end_inset

.
 In this form, the function is known as the beta transform, and is often
 called the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-transformation, presenting a typesetting challenge to search engines when
 used in titles of papers.
 The orbit of a point 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 in the beta shift is identical to the orbit of a point 
\begin_inset Formula $u=2x/\beta$
\end_inset

 in the beta transformation.
 Explicitly comparing to the beta shift of eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:downshift"

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T_{\beta}^{n}\left(x\right)=\frac{\beta}{2}t_{\beta}^{n}\left(\frac{2x}{\beta}\right)
\]

\end_inset

The beta shift and the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-transformation are essentially 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the same function
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

; this text works almost exclusively with the beta shift, and is thus idiosyncra
tic, as it flouts the much more common convention of working with the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-transformation.
 The primary reason is to retain contact with the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-shift being a subshift of the full shift.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Beta Transformation Literature Review and References
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-transformation, in the form of 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{\beta}\left(x\right)=\beta x\,\mod1$
\end_inset

 has been well-studied over the decades.
 The beta-expansion 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:down-bits"

\end_inset

 was introduced by A.
 Renyi
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Renyi57"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, who demonstrates the existence of the invariant measure.
 The ergodic properties of the transform were proven by W.
 Parry
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Parry60"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, who also shows that the system is weakly mixing.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An explicit expression for the invariant measure was independently obtained
 by A.O.
 Gel'fond
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Gelfond59"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 and by W.
 Parry
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Parry60"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\nu_{\beta}\left(y\right)=\frac{1}{F}\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\frac{\varepsilon_{n}\left(y\right)}{\beta^{n}}\label{eq:invariant measure}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{n}$
\end_inset

 is the digit sequence 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varepsilon_{n}\left(y\right)=\begin{cases}
0 & \mbox{ if }t_{\beta}^{n}\left(1\right)\le y\\
1 & \mbox{ otherwise}
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is a normalization constant.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the same way that a dyadic rational 
\begin_inset Formula $p/2^{n}$
\end_inset

 has two different binary expansions, one ending in all-zeros, and a second
 ending in all-ones, so one may also ask if and when a real number 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 might have more than one 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-expansion (for fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

).
 In general, it can; N.
 Sidorov shows that almost every number has a continuum of such expansions!
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Sidorov03"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Conversely, the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

univoke numbers
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 are those values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 for which there is only one, unique expansion for 
\begin_inset Formula $x=1$
\end_inset

.
 These are studied by De Vries.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DeVries06"
literal "true"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-transformation has been shown to have the same ergodicity properties as
 the Bernoulli shift.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Dajani97"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 The fact that the beta shift, and its subshifts are all ergodic is established
 by Climenhaga and Thompson.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Clim10"
literal "true"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An alternative to the notion of ergodicity is the notion of universality:
 a 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-expansion is universal if, for any given finite string of bits, that finite
 string occurs somewhere in the expansion.
 This variant of universality was introduced by Erdös and Komornik
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Erdos98"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 Its is shown by N.
 Sidorov that almost every 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-expansion is universal.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Sidorov02"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 Conversely, there are some values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 for which rational numbers have purely periodic 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-expansions;
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Adamczewski10"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 all such numbers are Pisot numbers.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Schmidt80"
literal "true"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The symbolic dynamics of the beta-transformation was analyzed by F.
 Blanchard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Blanchard89"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 A characterization of the periodic points are given by Bruno Maia
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Maia07"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 A discussion of various open problems with respect to the beta expansion
 is given by Akiyama.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Akiyama09"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When the beta expansion is expanded to the entire real-number line, one
 effectively has a representation of reals in a non-integer base.
 One may ask about arithmetic properties, such as the behavior of addition
 and multiplication, in this base - for example, the sum or product of two
 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-integers may have a fractional part! Bounds on the lengths of these fractional
 parts, and related topics, are explored by multiple authors.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Guimond01,Julien06,Hbaib13"
literal "true"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Certain values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 - generally, the Pisot numbers, generate fractal tilings,
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Thurston89,Berthe05,Ito05,Adamczewski10,Akiyama09"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 which are generalizations of the Rauzy fractal.
 An overview, with common terminology and definitions is provided by Akiyama.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Akiyama17"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 The tilings, sometimes called (generalized) Rauzy fractals, an be thought
 of as living in a direct product of Euclidean and 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-adic spaces.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Berthe04"
literal "true"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The set of finite beta-expansions constitutes a language, in the formal
 sense of model theory and computer science.
 This language is recursive (that is, decidable by a Turing machine), if
 and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 is a computable real number.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Simonsen11"
literal "true"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The zeta function, and a lap-counting function, are given by Lagarias
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Lagarias94"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 The Hausdorff dimension, the topological entropy and general notions of
 topological pressure arising from conditional variational principles is
 given by Daniel Thompson
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Thompson10"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 A proper background on this topic is given by Barreira and Saussol
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Barreira01"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
None of the topics or results cited above are made use of, or further expanded
 on, or even touched on below.
 That's mostly because what follows below is just a ...
 different perspective on the topic.
 Not intentionally so; it just happened to come out that way.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Symbolic Dynamics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A breif review of the Cantor
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Self-similarity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The full dyadic monoid is generated by the generators 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

.
 It consists of all finite-length strings of the form 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\gamma=g^{a_{1}}rg^{a_{2}}rg^{a_{3}}r\cdots rg^{a_{m}}
\]

\end_inset

for a finite-length list of positive integers 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(a_{1},a_{2},a_{3,}\cdots,a_{m}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Note that this list can be interpreted as a continued fraction; this establishe
s an isomorphism between the continued fractions and the dyadic monoid.
 This isomorphism is conventionally called the Minkowski question-mark function.
 We can be a bit more explicit.
 Write 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g_{\beta}\left(x\right)=\frac{x}{\beta}
\]

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r_{\beta}\left(x\right)=\frac{\beta}{2\left(\beta-1\right)}-x
\]

\end_inset

Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{\beta}\circ r_{\beta}=1$
\end_inset

 so that it is a reflection, and that 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{2}\left(x\right)=1-x$
\end_inset

 is the reflection of the unit interval.
 For strings of binary digits, the reflection performs the exchange of 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leftrightarrow1$
\end_inset

; its a mirroring symmetry.
 The above relationships then become
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g_{\beta}\circ\mbox{pdr}_{\beta}=\mbox{pdr}_{\beta}\circ g_{2}
\]

\end_inset

and
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r_{\beta}\circ\mbox{pdr}_{\beta}=\mbox{pdr}_{\beta}\circ r_{2}
\]

\end_inset

The symmetry under the dyadic monoid is simply the statement that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\gamma_{\beta}\circ\mbox{pdr}_{\beta}=\mbox{pdr}_{\beta}\circ\gamma_{2}
\]

\end_inset

for any 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 of the above form.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Beta expansions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Bernoulli process and it's relationship to the Cantor set provides the
 baseline to which the beta shift can be compared.
 The beta shift has a number of very striking differences, however, which
 manifet themselves in the structure of the beta transformations.
 This section will concern itself with what will be called the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

gaps
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, which, roughly speaking, are the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

spaces between numbers
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, or, perhaps, the lack-thereof.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
More precisely, again consider the binary expansion of a real number
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x=0.b_{0}b_{1}b_{2}\cdots
\]

\end_inset

The dyadic rationals, rationals in the form 
\begin_inset Formula $r=\left(2k+1\right)/2^{n}$
\end_inset

 have two equivalent representations:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r=0.b_{0}b_{1}b_{2}\cdots b_{n-2}1000\cdots
\]

\end_inset

and
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r=0.b_{0}b_{1}b_{2}\cdots b_{n-2}0111\cdots
\]

\end_inset

These are equivalent as real numbers; they are inequivalent as elements
 of the Cantor space 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{\omega}$
\end_inset

.
 The term 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

gap
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 flies to mind when one writes 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\frac{b_{n}}{3^{n+1}}
\]

\end_inset

the collection of such real numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 being the conventional Cantor set as it appears in the reals.
 It obviously has 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

gaps
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 These are the objects of study here.
 They have a natural interpretation in terms ot the infinite binary tree:
 a gap occurs whenever one makes a left-right decision in travelling down
 the tree.
 The left sub-tree is distinct from the right, and the gap is what lies
 in between.
 The word 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

gap
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is also interestng, as it suggests that the real numbers can be constructed
 from the Cantor set by 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

gluing together the gaps
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

: a nicely intuitive idea.
\end_layout

