\begin_layout Subsection
Orbits and measures
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The branch-points can be thought of as being 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

dense in the tree
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\left(\beta\right)<\infty$
\end_inset

.
 Intuitively, having dense branch-points, suggests that the corresponding
 map should have a positive measure on the real number line.
 In this case, one then expects the out-of-bounds measure to be roughly
 proportional to 
\begin_inset Formula $1/\ell\left(\beta\right)$
\end_inset

.
 This can be made precise.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Each alternative expansion arises from an alternative orbit.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 specify that alternative; that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 is a specific path down the binary tree.
 it is a sequence of left-right moves down the tree.
 Denote these as 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=\left(\gamma_{0},\gamma_{1},\gamma_{2},\cdots\right)$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{k}=0$
\end_inset

 for a left-move and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{k}=1$
\end_inset

 for a right move.
 Correspondingly, let 
\begin_inset Formula $(p_{0},p_{1},p_{2},\cdots)$
\end_inset

 be locations of the alternative choices in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-expansion along that particular path.
 The alternative orbit is then given by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tau_{n}\left(x\right)=\begin{cases}
T_{\beta}^{n}\left(x\right) & \mbox{ for }n<p_{0}\\
\left(1-\gamma_{0}\right)\beta T_{\beta}^{p_{0}-1}\left(x\right)+\gamma_{0}T_{\beta}^{p_{0}}\left(x\right) & \mbox{ for }n=p_{0}\\
T_{\beta}^{n-p_{0}}\left(\tau_{p_{0}}\left(x\right)\right) & \mbox{ for }p_{0}<n<p_{1}\\
\cdots & \cdots\\
\left(1-\gamma_{k}\right)\beta\tau_{n-1}\left(x\right)+\gamma_{k}T\left(\tau_{n-1}\left(x\right)\right) & \mbox{ for }n=p_{k}\\
T_{\beta}^{n-p_{k}}\left(\tau_{p_{k}}\left(x\right)\right) & \mbox{ for }p_{k}<n<p_{k+1}\\
\cdots & \cdots
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

This sequence has a corresponding bit string expansion
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\kappa_{n}\left(x\right)=\begin{cases}
0 & \mbox{ if }0\le\tau_{n}(x)<\frac{1}{2}\mbox{ and n\ensuremath{\ne p_{k}}}\\
1 & \mbox{ if }\frac{1}{2}\le\tau_{n}(x)\le1\mbox{ and n\ensuremath{\ne p_{k}}}\\
\gamma_{k} & \mbox{ if }n=p_{k}
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

By construction, one has that each of these bit strings provide an inequivalent
 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-expansion for the same 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 That is, one has, for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x=\frac{1}{2}\,\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\frac{\kappa_{n}\left(x\right)}{\beta^{n}}
\]

\end_inset

by construction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As there are an uncountable number of paths down the binary tree, the collection
 of such orbits 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{n}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 is also uncountable.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $l\left(\beta\right)<\infty$
\end_inset

, then one might reasonably expect that such orbits accumulate on the real
 number line with a non-zero measure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A few quick remarks on phrase 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

non-zero measure
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in the previous sentence.
 The various constructions in this text are meant to be understood as dynamical
 systems acting on the Cantor space 
\begin_inset Formula $\{0,1\}^{\omega}$
\end_inset

 endowed with the product topology.
 The topology is extedned to a sigma-algebra in the conventional way; denote
 this Borel algebra by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

.
 The open sets of this topology are the cylinder sets.
 Every such cylinder set has a positive Bernoulli measure, and when mapped
 to the unit inverval, by any map having the form of a 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-expansion, always results in an interval of finite measure.
 The action of 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\beta}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is well-defined on cylinder sets, and given that 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 is built out of 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\beta}$
\end_inset

, one can conclude that 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is also a map of cylinder sets.
 That is, the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau^{-1}:\mathcal{B\to\mathcal{B}}$
\end_inset

 is a map of the Borel algebra 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

, preserving all of the sigma-algebra properties of the product topology.
 It will have an associated invariant measure, the Ruelle-Frobenius-Perron
 measure, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{\beta}:\mathcal{B}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 It is invariant in that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{\beta}\circ\tau^{-1}\left(c\right)=\mu_{\beta}\left(c\right)$
\end_inset

 for all cylinders 
\begin_inset Formula $c\in\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

 having 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{\beta}\left(c\right)>0$
\end_inset

.
 This is just the standard defintion of a measure-preserving dynamical system.
 With that out of the way, it is straight-forward and entirely safe to treat
 numerical histogramming of the orbits of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{n}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 as being approximations to the true measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{\beta}$
\end_inset

.
