\begin_layout Subsection
Relations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The distance 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

 is directly related to likelihood of encountering a one followed by 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 zero's in a given string.
 This liklihood is directly accessible to computation.
 Starting with any number 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, a one will occur in the expansion if 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}\le T_{\beta}(x)\le1$
\end_inset

.
 A string of 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 zeros follow if 
\begin_inset Formula $0\le T_{\beta}^{j}(x)<\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $1<j\le m+1$
\end_inset

.
 The first condition is satisfied if 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1}{2\beta}\le x\le\frac{1}{\beta}\quad\mbox{ or }\quad\frac{1}{2}+\frac{1}{2\beta}\le x\le\frac{1}{2}+\frac{1}{\beta}\quad\mbox{or }\quad1+\frac{1}{2\beta}\le x\le1+\frac{1}{\beta}
\]

\end_inset

There are three pre-images, as the measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{\beta}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 is non-zero for values 
\begin_inset Formula $1<x$
\end_inset

.
 The second condition is satisfied if 
\begin_inset Formula $0\le\beta^{m}\left(T_{\beta}\left(x\right)-\frac{1}{2}\right)<\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

; that is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1}{2}\le T_{\beta}\left(x\right)<\frac{1}{2}\left(1+\frac{1}{\beta^{m}}\right)
\]

\end_inset

The intersection of these three intervals is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{1}{2\beta}\le x\le\frac{1}{2\beta}\left(1+\frac{1}{\beta^{m}}\right) & \quad\mbox{ or }\\
\frac{1}{2}+\frac{1}{2\beta}\le x\le\frac{1}{2}+\frac{1}{2\beta}\left(1+\frac{1}{\beta^{m}}\right) & \quad\mbox{ or }\\
1+\frac{1}{2\beta}\le x\le1+\frac{1}{2\beta}\left(1+\frac{1}{\beta^{m}}\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The corresponding cylinders are to be sampled out of the measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{\beta}$
\end_inset

, That is, the probability 
\begin_inset Formula $p\left(\beta\right)$
\end_inset

 of encountering such an 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 corresponds to
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p\left(\beta\right)=\int_{a}^{b}d\mu_{\beta}+\int_{c}^{d}d\mu_{\beta}+\int_{e}^{f}d\mu_{\beta}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[a,b\right]$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[c,d\right]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[e,f\right]$
\end_inset

 are the three pre-images above.
 This gives the expectation value for the distance between such cylinders:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{0}^{4/3}\ell\left(\beta\right)d\mu_{\beta}=\frac{1}{p\left(\beta\right)}
\]

\end_inset

As in an earlier section, 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\left(\beta\right)=\lim_{n\to\infty}\ell_{n}\left(\beta\right)$
\end_inset

 has an a priori 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

-dependence, and so, when considering the distance between cylinders in
 a thrermalized orbit, one must use the corresponding thermalized measure
 for sampling.
 In this sense, this expression is a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

more correct
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 definition of the average distance between branch points, as opposed to
 the one explored earlier, namely 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\ell}\left(\beta\right)=\int_{0}^{1}\ell\left(\beta\right)dx$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

